+    <h1>How to Read a Secondary Source</h1>
+    <p class="lede">A secondary source talks <em>about</em> the law rather than being the law. It is a map, not the territory: you use it to find and understand primary authority, and with rare exceptions you do not cite it as the law itself. Reading one well is the Question Method applied to a page — every part of the page exists to answer a certain kind of question.</p>
+    <div class="howto"><b>How to use this:</b> the page below is a demonstration encyclopedia entry (fictional, on the tenant-heat problem you have met in other modules). Click each highlighted part to learn what it is and how a researcher reads it. Then work the engagement steps and the knowledge check underneath.</div>
+
+    <div class="grid">
+      <article class="src" aria-label="Demonstration encyclopedia entry (fictional)">
+        <span class="src-tag">Demonstration — fictional encyclopedia entry</span>
+        <div class="src-body">
+          <button class="hot block" data-part="finding" type="button" aria-expanded="false">
+            <span class="toc-line">Landlord and Tenant &rsaquo; Duties of the Landlord &rsaquo; Habitability &rsaquo; § 412</span>
+            <span class="sec-head">§ 412. Duty to Provide Heat; Time to Repair</span>
+          </button>
+
+          <button class="hot block" data-part="narrative" type="button" aria-expanded="false">
+            <p>In most jurisdictions, a residential landlord owes the tenant a duty to keep the premises fit for habitation, and the supply of heat during the cold months is among the conditions courts treat as essential to fitness.<span class="fn-no">1</span> Where heat fails, the landlord is generally required to restore it within a reasonable time; what is reasonable turns on the severity of the season, the notice the landlord received, and the availability of repair.<span class="fn-no">2</span> A minority of jurisdictions fix the obligation by statute or housing code, specifying minimum temperatures the premises must maintain.<span class="fn-no">3</span></p>
+          </button>
+
+          <button class="hot block" data-part="footnotes" type="button" aria-expanded="false">
+            <div class="fnblock">
+              <p><span class="fn-no">1</span> See, e.g., <i>Marsh v. Golden Rentals</i> (recognizing heat as an essential service under the duty of habitability) (fictional).</p>
+              <p><span class="fn-no">2</span> <i>Tinsley v. Vista Prop. Mgmt.</i> (reasonable time measured from notice to the landlord) (fictional).</p>
+              <p><span class="fn-no">3</span> See the minimum-temperature housing codes collected in the annotation cited below.</p>
+            </div>
+          </button>
+
+          <button class="hot block" data-part="currency" type="button" aria-expanded="false">
+            <p class="currency">Current through the 2025 supplement · updated annually · check the pocket part in print</p>
+          </button>
+
+          <button class="hot block" data-part="apparatus" type="button" aria-expanded="false">
+            <div class="apparatus"><b>Research references</b>
+              Cross-reference: § 418 (Tenant remedies for breach). See also the ALR annotation, <i>Landlord's Failure to Provide Heat</i>, collecting authority by jurisdiction; Restatement (Second) of Property: Landlord &amp; Tenant.
+            </div>
+          </button>
+        </div>
+      </article>
+
+      <aside class="explain" aria-label="Explanation">
+        <h2 id="ex-title">Click a part of the entry</h2>
+        <div class="body" id="ex-body" role="status" aria-live="polite">
+          <p>Each highlighted region of the entry is one of the five components every secondary source shares. Click one — or Tab to it and press Enter — to see what it does and how the method reads it.</p>
+        </div>
+        <p class="seen" id="ex-seen">Explored 0 of 5 components</p>
+      </aside>
+    </div>
+
+    <section class="engage" aria-labelledby="engage-h">
+      <h2 id="engage-h">How to engage with the source</h2>
+      <ol>
+        <li><b>Match the source type to your question type.</b> A no-clue exploratory question wants an encyclopedia; a foundational question wants a treatise; a survey question across jurisdictions wants an ALR annotation, a Restatement, or a 50-state survey. Choosing the right secondary source for the question you are holding is the first efficiency the method buys you.</li>
+        <li><b>Navigate — do not read end to end.</b> Use the table of contents and index to jump to the section that answers your <em>current</em> question.</li>
+        <li><b>Mine the footnotes in the order your question dictates.</b> When a passage's footnotes point to half a dozen cases, read the one that answers the question you are holding right now, and log the rest as later questions with their citations noted.</li>
+        <li><b>Confirm against primary authority, and check currency.</b> A secondary source can be out of date, can oversimplify, or can be wrong. Go read the primary authority it points to, and note the "current through" date.</li>
+        <li><b>Cite primary authority, not the secondary source.</b> With narrow exceptions, you build the argument on the authority the source led you to.</li>
+      </ol>
+
+      <div class="kc">
+        <p class="q">Your question is: <i>"How do the fifty states handle a landlord's duty to provide heat?"</i> Which secondary source does that question point to?</p>
+        <div class="opts" id="kc-opts" role="group" aria-label="Pick the source that matches the question"></div>
+        <div class="fb" id="kc-fb" role="status" aria-live="polite"></div>
+      </div>
+    </section>
