+    <h1>Type the Question</h1>
+    <p class="lede">Naming a question's type tells you where to look and how far along you are. For each question below, name the type — then pick the source family that type points to. The feedback explains the tell in the question's own wording.</p>
+    <div class="howto"><b>How to use this:</b> two moves per question. First classify it (definitional, exploratory, focusing, or application), then match it to a source. Every question can be typed from its wording alone — that is the skill.</div>
+
+    <div class="legend" aria-label="The four question types">
+      <div><b>Definitional</b>What a word or phrase means. Dictionary or general search for orientation; the statute's definitions section, a regulation, or case law when precision is critical.</div>
+      <div><b>Exploratory</b>What the landscape looks like. No-clue &rarr; encyclopedia or general search; foundational &rarr; treatise; survey &rarr; ALR, Restatement, 50-state survey.</div>
+      <div><b>Focusing</b>What the specific governing rule, standard, or test is — the move from secondary to primary authority.</div>
+      <div><b>Application</b>How the rule operates on specific facts: cases with similar facts, or build the rule from multiple sources when nothing is on point.</div>
+    </div>
+
+    <div class="scorebar"><span id="score">0 answered</span><div class="prog"><span id="progfill"></span></div><span id="tally"></span></div>
+    <div id="deck"></div>
+    <div class="done" id="done" role="status" aria-live="polite"></div>
+
+    <div id="export-slot"></div>
